<p><b>Valentin Fyodorovich Bulgakov</b> (<a href="/wiki/Russian_language" title="Russian language">Russian</a>: <span lang="ru" xml:lang="ru">Валентин Фёдорович Булгаков</span>; 25 November 1886 <a href="/wiki/Kuznetsk" title="Kuznetsk">Kuznetsk</a>, <a href="/wiki/Russian_Empire" title="Russian Empire">Russian Empire</a> – 22 September 1966 <a href="/wiki/Yasnaya_Polyana" title="Yasnaya Polyana">Yasnaya Polyana</a>, <a href="/wiki/Tula_Oblast" title="Tula Oblast">Tula Oblast</a>, <a href="/wiki/Soviet_Union" title="Soviet Union">Soviet Union</a>) was the last secretary of <a href="/wiki/Leo_Tolstoy" title="Leo Tolstoy">Leo Tolstoy</a> and his biographer. He was director of a number of literary museums and was engaged in <a href="/wiki/Tolstoyan" title="Tolstoyan" class="mw-redirect">Tolstoyan</a>, <a href="/wiki/Pacifist" title="Pacifist" class="mw-redirect">pacifist</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Anti-communist" title="Anti-communist" class="mw-redirect">anti-communist</a> activities. He was imprisoned by both the <a href="/wiki/Tsarist" title="Tsarist" class="mw-redirect">Tsarist</a> and <a href="/wiki/Soviet_Union" title="Soviet Union">Soviet</a> regimes and was a <a href="/wiki/Nazi" title="Nazi" class="mw-redirect">Nazi</a> <a href="/wiki/Concentration_camp" title="Concentration camp" class="mw-redirect">concentration camp</a> survivor. During the final 20 years of his life he was head of the <a href="/wiki/Yasnaya_Polyana" title="Yasnaya Polyana">Yasnaya Polyana</a> museum.</p>
<p></p>
